<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=99019022887111></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99019022887111><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=item.html?item=5845&mid=99019022887111>Improvement, not reduction.</a> <a id=fs8 href=item.html?item=5845&mid=99019022887111#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=353><span id=Sage>Tehom</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>135 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, May 18th 8:50 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.64]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>If the haste % was a reduction of delay, then yes, the delay would be zero. However, think of it as its name implies - an improvement in speed. What is a 100% speed improvement? Where X is the rate at which you hit: X + (1.00)X = 2X. Doubling. 200%? X + (2.00)X = 3X. Trippling. And so on. You can then either think of that as a multiplication on the delay (.5, .33, .25, etc), or you can just think of it as hitting appropriately faster.<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
